Helper Functions

PlotPower <- function(funcDF, xargString, yargString, targetString, sizeString, title) {
  
  # Gets the number of unique values from the target column
  targets=unique(power[,targetString])
  n_targets = length(targets)
  
  #col=rgb(red=0.2, green=0.2, blue=1.0, alpha=0.2)
  
  # Sets the color palette
  col.vec <- rep(
    hsv(0.5, 0.75, seq(.45,.90,length.out = n_targets), alpha=0.3),
    targets=unique(power[,targetString])
  )
  
  # Sets the size of each dot
  obj.size <- seq(0.4,1.5,length.out = length(power[,sizeString]))
  
  # Plots the graph
  plot(
    x = power[,xargString],
    y = power[,yargString],
    xlab = xargString,
    ylab = yargString,
    main = title,
    type = "p",
    lty = 1, lwd = 1,
    pch = 16,
    cex = obj.size, cex.axis = 1, cex.lab = 1,
    col = col.vec
  )
  
  par(mar=c(2, 4, 4, 8), xpd=TRUE)
  
  legend(
    "bottomright",
    inset=c(0, 0),
    bty = "n",
    pch=c(16,16,16),
    col=col.vec,
    legend=targets
  )
}

# This function creates a new column called 'Renewable' and labels each energy
# type as either renewable or non-renewable according to EIA.gov"
GetRenewable <- function(funcDF) {
  funcDF <- funcDF %>% 
  mutate(renewable = case_when(
    (primary_fuel == "Hydro") ~ "Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Solar") ~ "Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Geothermal") ~ "Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Biomass") ~ "Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Wind") ~ "Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Coal") ~ "Non-Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Cogeneration") ~"Non-Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Gas")~"Non-Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Nuclear") ~"Non-Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Other") ~ "Non-Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Petcoke") ~"Non-Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Storage")~"Non-Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Waste") ~"Non-Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Wave and Tidal") ~"Non-Renewable",
    (primary_fuel == "Oil") ~"Non-Renewable"
  )) 
  
  return(data.frame(funcDF))
}

# This function gets the age of the power plants and puts that into a new column
GetFacilityAge <- function(funcDF) {
  
  currentYear = as.integer(format(Sys.Date(), "%Y"))

  return(data.frame(transform(funcDF, facilityAge = (currentYear - floor(commissioning_year)))))
}

# This function creates a new 
GetHighIncome <- function(funcDF) {
  funcDF <- funcDF %>% 
  mutate(income = case_when(
    (gdpPerCapita >= 12696) ~ "HighIncome",
    (gdpPerCapita < 12696) ~ "LowIncome",
  )) 
  
  return(data.frame(funcDF))
}
power <- read.csv('globalpowerplant/global_power_plant_database.csv',

My Hypothesis

Higher income countries are more likely to utilize renewable energy sources since they have more income and financial resources to use in order to invest in more renewable resources and renewable resource research. So we should see higher income countries utilize more renewable resources.

Conclusion - Renewable vs Non-Renewable Percentages

In the ratio plots we can see that there is overall more blue bars (renewable energy sources) being used by lower income countries, and more red bars (non-renewable energy sources) being used by higher income countries. This disproves my initial hypothesis.

Conclusion - Age of Facility

We can see by the two distributions below that the average ages of lower income countries leans more towards newer power plant facilities, while the higher income countries have a more even distribution which means they are using more older facilities. This distributions further disproves my initial hypothesis that higher income countries would invest more infrastructure funding towards newer, renewable power sources but thats clearly not the case.
